y investigates Penang Chinese religion as the product of a specific history, rather than presenting an overgeneralized overview that claims to represent a single "Chinese religion."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362564840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503625648423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503625648/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles